SIMPLE: invagination
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invagination
<hw>In*vag`i*na"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. pref.
<ets>in-</ets> + <ets>vagina</ets> sheath.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The condition of an invaginated
organ or part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The inward movement of the wall of a tissue or cell,
to form a cavity; also, the cavity thus formed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Biol.,
Embryology)</fld> <def>The inward movement of one part of the wall of a
blastula, to form a gastrula; the process of gastrulation, in which
layers of the ovum are differentiated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In <stype>embolic invagination</stype>, one half of the
blastosphere is pushed in towards the other half, producing an embryonic
form known as a <xex>gastrula</xex>. -- In <stype>epibolic
invagination</stype>, a phenomenon in the development of some
invertebrate ova, the epiblast appears to grow over or around the
hypoblast.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invalescence</ent>⟦br⟧
